  "local_port": 48572,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Though people tell me I am pretty, why do I sometimes feel not pretty or I don't like what I see in the mirror?",
  "response": "It's completely normal to feel this way at times, even if others perceive you as pretty. Our feelings about our appearance can be influenced by many factors, including:\n\n1. **Self-Perception**: How we see ourselves can differ from how others see us. We might focus on what we perceive as flaws, which can be magnified in our own minds.\n\n2. **Mood and Mental Health**: Our mood and mental health can greatly influence how we view ourselves. On days when we're feeling down, we might be more critical of our appearance.\n\n3. **Societal Standards**: Media and societal standards of beauty can be overwhelming and unrealistic. Constantly comparing ourselves to these standards can make us feel inadequate or unattractive.\n\n4. **Internalized Criticism**: Negative comments from others, even if they were said long ago, can stick with us and affect how we see ourselves.\n\n5. **Personal Standards**: We might hold ourselves to very high standards that are hard to meet, leading to feelings of dissatisfaction with our appearance.\n\nHere are some ways to address these feelings:\n\n- **Positive Affirmations**: Regularly remind yourself of your positive qualities, both physical and non-physical.\n- **Mindfulness and Self-Compassion**: Practice being kind to yourself and recognizing that everyone has days when they don't feel their best.\n- **Limit Exposure to Unrealistic Standards**: Try to reduce the time you spend on social media or watching shows that promote unrealistic beauty standards.\n- **Seek Professional Help**: If these feelings are persistent and affecting your quality of life, talking to a therapist can be very helpful.\n\nRemember, beauty is subjective and diverse. What's most important is how you feel about yourself and nurturing a positive self-image.",
